<p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6c757d; margin-top: 0.5rem; text-align: center;">
  Video: How QR code payments work in China's cashless economy.
</p>


    
    <p>Before my first trip to China, a friend asked me, “How much cash should I bring?”<br />
    “I don’t know,” I said. “Maybe a few hundred pounds?”<br />
    She laughed. “You won’t need it. Just your phone.”</p>

    <p>I didn’t believe her. In London, I use my phone for some things — contactless payments on the Tube, ordering takeaway. But cash and cards are still everywhere. You can’t buy a newspaper from a street vendor with Apple Pay. You can’t pay for a bus ticket with a wave of your phone if you’re not on a specific route.</p>

    <p>So I packed my wallet anyway. I even went to the bank to get crisp new notes.</p>

    <p>But on my first morning in Shanghai, I decided to try an experiment. I left my wallet in the hotel safe. I took only my phone — and a photocopy of my passport just in case.</p>

    <p>I walked to a convenience store. Picked up a bottle of water and a rice ball. The cashier pointed at a QR code. I opened <strong>Alipay (zhīfùbǎo)</strong> — which I’d set up the night before, using my foreign credit card. Scanned. The screen flashed “Payment successful — ¥9.80”. That was it. No fumbling for coins, no signature, no PIN.</p>

    <p>I felt a strange thrill. <em>This is how they live every day.</em></p>

    <p>Over the next two weeks, I pushed the experiment further.</p>

    <p>I took a ride‑hailing app (China’s version of Uber) from my hotel to the Bund. The app charged me automatically — I didn’t even have to press “pay”. I ordered lunch from a dumpling shop through a food delivery app. Twenty minutes later, a scooter rider handed me a warm bag. I bought a high‑speed train ticket from Shanghai to Hangzhou on my phone — no ticket office, no queue, just a QR code on my screen.</p>

    <p>By day four, I’d forgotten my wallet even existed.</p>

    <p>The most surprising moment came in a small alley in Hangzhou. An old woman was roasting sweet potatoes in a charcoal drum. The smell was incredible. I asked how much — “Six yuan,” she said. I pulled out my phone, expecting her to shake her head. Instead, she pointed to a faded QR code taped to the side of her cart. I scanned, paid with <strong>Alipay (zhīfùbǎo)</strong>, and walked away with a steaming sweet potato.</p>

    <p>That’s when it hit me: <em>this isn’t just convenience. It’s infrastructure.</em> From a street vendor to a five‑star hotel, from a museum ticket booth to a hospital registration desk — everyone, everywhere, expects you to pay with your phone.</p>

    <p>One evening, I tried to find a limit. I booked a hotel room, ordered dinner, bought a ticket for a light show, paid for a shared bike, and sent money to a friend — all on my phone, all within an hour. No card swiped. No cash handed over.</p>

    <p>Later, when I needed to split dinner with new friends, I used <strong>WeChat Pay (wēixìn zhīfù)</strong>. They scanned my QR code, and the money appeared in my account instantly. No awkward “I’ll get it next time” — just seamless digital trust.</p>

    <p>Back in London, after my trip, I went to a café. I automatically reached for my phone to pay. The cashier looked at me strangely. “Card or cash only,” she said. I fumbled for my wallet. It felt clumsy, slow, old‑fashioned.</p>

    <p>I realised then: China hadn’t just been a trip. It had reset my default.</p>

